Protein synthesis is a complex process which starts with mRNA leaving the nucleus via a special tunnel, called nuclear pore, and travelling through the cytoplasm to the ribosome. Then, the mRNA bases are read in triplets called codons which are matched to their complementary anticodons held by tRNA molecules. Subsequently, amino acids are linked together to form a protein molecule starting with a START codon in the P-site and ending with a STOP codon at the A-site.

The journey of protein synthesis begins with mRNA exiting nucleus via nuclear pores. In the cytoplasm, mRNA's codons are read in triplets and matched to their complementary anticodons on tRNA molecules. After that, amino acids are joined together to form proteins, commencing with a START codon on the P-site and concluding with a STOP codon at the A-site.

Protein synthesis starts its path with mRNA leaving the nucleus via the nuclear pore, then it moves across the cytoplasm where its codons are read in triplets and matched up with their tRNA anticodons. Following that, amino acids are linked together while forming a protein molecule beginning with START codon at P-site and finishing off with STOP codon at A-site.

Protein synthesis takes off after mRNA abandons nucleus via nuclear pores. Then, mRNA's codons get read in groups of three which get combined to their equivalent tRNA anticodons. Subsequently, amino acids come together while building a protein molecule starting from START codon at P-site concluding in STOP codon at A-site.

Protein synthesis kicks off when mRNA takes off from nucleus via nuclear pores. From there on, mRNA's codons get read in triplets getting married to their opposite counterparts found on tRNA molecules. Following this step, amino acids team up while assembling a protein molecule beginning with START codon on P-site and winding up with STOP codon on A-site.

First, mRNA leaves the nucleus through a nuclear pore so it can go on its wild adventure! It then travels to the ribosome or else enters the rough endoplasmic reticulum. Then, codons are read by rRNA in order to begin assembling the protein, before tRNA anticodons recognize complementary codons on the mRNA. Following that, amino acids become linked together by attaching each new amino acid to the tRNA. This process slowly builds up, until a STOP codon is reached and the protein is complete! Wow!

It all starts with mRNA escaping from the nucleus on an escape ship! The next step is to get to the ribosome quickly so that codons can be read and matched up with their antisense codons. Then, tRNA carries the complementary (U=A, C+G) anticodon which recognizes the complementary codon of the mRNA. This is followed by a magical process where the corresponding amino acids on the tRNA form bonds with new corresponding amino acids until a START codon is found. Finally, a STOP codon causes the completion of the protein - how amazing!

Selective permeability is used to allow certain substances to move across the cell membrane, while passive transport occurs when substances move from an area of higher concentration to an area of lower concentration.
Osmosis is a type of diffusion where water molecules cross the cell membrane while facilitated diffusion occurs when the membrane controls the pathway for a particle to enter or leave a cell.

Active transport requires energy and involves moving substances from an area of low to high concentration, or against the concentration gradient. Pumps and carrier proteins are also used for transporting charged particles such as sodium and potassium ions.
Membrane-assisted transport can take many forms, such as exocytosis, endocytosis, phagocytosis and pinocytosis, allowing large molecules and liquid droplets to be moved in or out of the cell.
Channel proteins are formed within the cell membrane, enabling specific molecules or substances to move into or out of the cell in an energy-efficient way.

Protein channels or channel proteins allow for the movement of specific molecules or substances into or out of the cell.

Selective permeability is used by the cell membrane to allow certain substances to move across, and passive transport allows for the diffusion of water through osmosis. Facilitated diffusion occurs when the membrane controls the pathway for a particle to enter or leave the cell, while active transport uses energy and pumps to move particles in or out. Membrane-assisted transport can also occur when the membrane of the vesicle fuses with the cell membrane to push out molecules, or when vesicles form around large molecules or liquid droplets as in exocytosis, endocytosis, phagocytosis and pinocytosis. Lastly, protein channels facilitate a specific molecule's movement into or out of the cell.

Cell membranes use a process called selective permeability to control which substances can pass through them. Substances are then moved across either passively, using osmosis for example, or actively using pumps and energy. Additionally, membrane-assisted transport occurs when vesicles are formed around a substance and then fuse with the cell membrane such as in exocytosis, endocytosis, phagocytosis and pinocytosis. Lastly, protein channels or channel proteins are used to move specific molecules or substances into or out of the cell.
Selective permeability is used by the cell membrane to make sure only good things cross over - so if we are nice, only nice things will pass! (ironic)
Passive transport occurs when substances move from an area of higher concentration to an area of lower concentration aka 'following the party' (ironic).
Osmosis is the diffusion of water across the cell membrane, but it's not quite like a door opening and closing in your house - think more like a balloon expanding and contracting (ironic).
Facilitated diffusion can be thought of as a highway with tolls, allowing certain molecules to pass but charging them for it (ironic).

It takes energy for active transport when a cell uses energy to move a substance across the cell membrane, and/or a substance moves from an area of low to high concentration - like driving up a mountain (ironic).
Pumps are used to move charged particles through membranes using energy and carrier proteins, like pumping gasoline in your car (ironic).
Membrane-assisted transport is kind of like a vacuum cleaner sucking molecules out of the cell as in exocytosis (ironic).
Membrane-assisted transport is like a vacuum cleaner ingesting molecules into the cell as in endocytosis (ironic).
Membrane-assisted transport can be seen as vesicles forming around large molecules as if they were scared citizens gathering in a safe place during war - phagocytosis (ironic).
Membrane-assisted transport appears as if liquid droplets are formed around vesicles - like drinking from a straw (ironic).
Selective permeability is used by the cell membrane to control the speed of molecules entering and exiting the cell.
Passive transport occurs when molecules move from an area of low concentration to an area of high concentration.
Osmosis is the diffusion of substances across the cell membrane using a type of energy called 'osmotic potential'.
Facilitated diffusion occurs when a particle is forced into or out of a cell.
Active transport occurs when cells use specific proteins to move molecules in or out of the cell.
Pumps are used to move particles like sodium and potassium ions through membranes without having to expend energy.
Membrane-assisted transport occurs when vesicles fuse with the outer layer of the cell membrane, allowing for large molecules to escape as in exocytosis.
Membrane-assisted transport involves a vesicle engulfing large molecules as in endocytosis.
Membrane-assisted transport is also used for phagocytosis, where vesicles are formed around solid particles.
Membrane-assisted transport is also used for pinocytosis, where vesicles are formed around liquid droplets.

Selective permeability is a process used by cells to control the movement of substances across the cell membrane! It involves the use of special 'magical' particles to attract certain molecules and repel others!
Passive transport occurs when large molecules magically move from an area of higher concentration to an area of lower concentration, using the power of 'quantum levitation'!
Osmosis is a process where water can seemingly defy gravity and travel up through the cell membrane! This happens due to the mysterious 'osmotic force'!
Facilitated diffusion happens when a cell uses 'teleportation' to transfer molecules from one place to another!
Active transport is a process where molecules are able to move from an area of low to high concentration, or against the concentration gradient - all thanks to the magical power of 'anti-gravity!'
Pumps are used to move charged particles like sodium and potassium ions through membranes using energy and what experts call 'hyper-speed!'
Membrane-assisted transport means that the membrane of the vesicle fuses with the cell membrane in such an amazing way that it forces large molecules out of the cell as in exocytosis!
Endocytosis is a process where molecules are engulfed by the cell membrane, using 'invisibility cloaks'!
Phagocytosis is a process where vesicles are formed around large molecules, through a mysterious process known as 'spontaneous generation'!
Pinocytosis is a process where vesicles are formed around liquid droplets using the arcane art of 'magnetism!'
Protein channels or channel proteins allow for the movement of specific molecules or substances into or out of the cell using ancient techniques called 'alchemy!'
